<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n25036m"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25036m">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25036m"> 36(m)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Old Bailey <small>Black</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n25036m"><li>FW 85.26 </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/lexd.htm#n25036m">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/d/l39d.htm#n25036m">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n25036m">MS BL 47472-266</ms> </li><li>JJA 46:098 <a name="dd5" href="../../ff/fdra/dda.htm#dd5">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/d/dd5.htm#n25036m">Draft: I.4&sect;1.5</a>/2.5</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">We now leave the town <font color="green">[of Howth]</font> to make our way to the <mark>Old Bailey</mark> lighthouse. <small> Weston St. John Joyce, <a name="WSJND" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#WSJND"><cite title="source">The Neighbourhood of Dublin</cite></a> (1921) 326</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Joyce conflates the Bailey at Howth with the &lsquo;Old Bailey&rsquo;, the Central Criminal Court of England and Wales, so-called from the street on which it stands. The Howth Bailey is the ancient fortress with fosse and line of circumvallation, the former residence of King Criffan, whose death took place (according to the <cite>Annals of the Four Masters</cite>) in the ninth year of the Christian era. Criffan (of whom many extraordinary tales are recorded) was reputed buried under a cairn at the top of the Hill of Howth. </mm> </dd></dl>
